\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. L. caerulea} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl.} 174 (1753). Up to 2 m, glabrous or more or less hairy. Twigs with solid pith. Bark on the older branches yellowish-brown to reddish, flaking. Leaves 2·5-7 × 1·2-3 cm, usually elliptical, sometimes obovate, ovate or oblong, acute or subacute. Peduncle 7-11 mm. Corolla 12-16 mm, yellowish-white, infundibuliform, with a gibbous, pubescent tube. Bracts linear, longer than the bracteoles; bracteoles connate in a tubular cupule enclosing the ovaries, later developing and forming, with the paired ovaries, a succulent, dark blue, compound fruit.{\i  N.E. Europe; also from the Pyrenees to Bulgaria & S.W. Czechoslovakia, mainly in the mountains.} Al Au Bu Cz Fe Ga Ge He Hs It Ju Rm Rs (N, B, C, W) Su [No].
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28   Very variable in hairiness of twigs, leaves and corolla.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28   ({\b a}) Subsp. {\b caerulea}: Twigs glabrous or sparsely hairy. Leaves glabrous or slightly hairy beneath, mostly along midrib. Corolla-tube wide, about twice as long as the limb. 2n = 18. {\i Throughout the range of the species, but rare in the northeast.}
\par 

\pard\f0\fs28   ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b pallasii} (Ledeb.) Browicz,{\i  Bot. Jour. Linn. Soc.}{\b  68}: 278 (1974) ({\i L. pallasii} Ledeb., {\i L. baltica} Pojark.): Twigs with a more or less dense, short tomentum, and with scattered long hairs up to 2 mm. Leaves more or less hairy on both surfaces, glabrescent above. Corolla-tube narrow, 2-3 times as long as limb.{\i  N.E. Europe; a few stations in the Alps}.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28   {\b L. altaica} Pallas,{\i  Fl. Ross.}{\b  1}({\b 1}): 58 (1784), recorded from N. & E. Russia, is probably only a variant of subsp. ({\b a}), differing in the narrower and longer corolla-tube and ellipsoid fruits.
